    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="300"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d300">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/4107</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2251</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-02">March 2,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received March 20.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Embassy’s despatch No. 2188 of
                    February 18, 1944, in regard to the China Defence League (relief organization
                    headed by Madame Sun Yat-sen), I have the honor to enclose a copy of airgram No.
                    A–7, February 14, 6 p.m. from the Consulate at Kweilin<note n="91"
                        xml:id="d300fn91">Not printed.</note> regarding the disposition by Madame
                    Sun Yat-sen of relief funds for work in south China.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="italic">Summary</hi>. Mr. Service states that he has been informed
                        in the strictest confidence by an American member of United China Relief
                        that Madame Sun has specified that one-third of a sum of approximately
                        CN$400,000 from her Kwantung Relief Committee in Chungking <pb facs="0385"
                            n="371" xml:id="pg_371"/> be paid to the Chinese Communist forces
                        operating in the area north and east of Hong Kong for relief purposes in the
                        region under their control. The other two-thirds is to be divided between
                        the Canton International Medical Service Corps and the Kwangtung
                        International Relief Committee. <hi rend="italic">End of Summary.</hi>
                    </p>
                </quote>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
